Here are the public test cases for feature1_1_filter_by_name:
{
  "description": "Selecting containers by an explicit allow-list of names. A name selector is built from a list of target names layered on top of a base selector that admits everything. A candidate is admitted only when its name equals one of the target names, where the comparison also succeeds against the candidate name with its first character removed (to tolerate a leading path separator on the reported name). When the target name list is empty the selector imposes no name restriction and the base selector decides alone (admitting every candidate). Output lists each candidate as its name and whether it was admitted.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "names",
        "names": [
          "test"
        ],
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "test"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=test included=true\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "names",
        "names": [
          "test"
        ],
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "NoTest"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=NoTest included=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature1_2_filter_by_enable_label:
{
  "description": "Restricting selection to containers that explicitly carry an opt-in enable marker. Each candidate exposes an enable state as a pair: a boolean value plus a presence flag indicating whether the marker was set at all. The selector admits a candidate only when the marker is present, regardless of whether its value is true or false; when the marker is absent the candidate is rejected. Output lists each candidate as its name and whether it was admitted.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "enable_label",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "a",
            "enabled": {
              "value": true,
              "present": true
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=a included=true\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "enable_label",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "c",
            "enabled": {
              "value": false,
              "present": false
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=c included=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature1_3_filter_by_disabled_label:
{
  "description": "Excluding only containers that explicitly opt out via the enable marker. Each candidate exposes an enable state as a pair: a boolean value plus a presence flag. The selector rejects a candidate only when the marker is present and its value is the opt-out value (false); in every other situation (marker present and true, or marker absent entirely) the candidate is admitted. Output lists each candidate as its name and whether it was admitted.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "disabled_label",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "b",
            "enabled": {
              "value": false,
              "present": true
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=b included=false\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "disabled_label",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "c",
            "enabled": {
              "value": false,
              "present": false
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=c included=true\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature1_4_filter_by_scope:
{
  "description": "Restricting selection to containers that belong to a specific named scope. A scope selector is built from a target scope string. Each candidate exposes its scope as a pair: a string value plus a presence flag indicating whether a scope was assigned. The selector admits a candidate only when the candidate has a scope present and that scope equals the target scope; a mismatched scope or an absent scope causes rejection. Output lists each candidate as its name and whether it was admitted.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "scope",
        "scope": "testscope",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "a",
            "scope": {
              "value": "testscope",
              "present": true
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=a included=true\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "scope",
        "scope": "testscope",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "b",
            "scope": {
              "value": "nottestscope",
              "present": true
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=b included=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature1_5_composite_filter:
{
  "description": "The composite selector used to choose update targets, assembled from several layers: an explicit name allow-list, an optional requirement that the opt-in enable marker be present, an optional scope restriction, and an always-applied exclusion of containers whose enable marker explicitly opts out. The opt-out exclusion is evaluated first, so a container that explicitly opts out is rejected before any other layer is consulted. Each candidate exposes a name and an enable state (value plus presence flag). This case configures the selector with a name allow-list only. Output lists each candidate as its name and whether it survived the full chain.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "build",
        "names": [
          "test"
        ],
        "enable_label": false,
        "scope": "",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "Invalid",
            "enabled": {
              "value": false,
              "present": false
            }
          },
          {
            "name": "test",
            "enabled": {
              "value": false,
              "present": false
            }
          },
          {
            "name": "Invalid",
            "enabled": {
              "value": true,
              "present": true
            }
          },
          {
            "name": "test",
            "enabled": {
              "value": true,
              "present": true
            }
          },
          {
            "name": "x",
            "enabled": {
              "value": false,
              "present": true
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=Invalid included=false\ncontainer=test included=true\ncontainer=Invalid included=false\ncontainer=test included=true\ncontainer=x included=false\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature1_6_base_predicates:
{
  "description": "The two base selection predicates that the larger selectors are built upon. One is an unconditional admit-all predicate that accepts every candidate regardless of its attributes. The other is a self-identification predicate that admits a candidate only when it reports itself as an instance of the update agent. Each candidate reports a name plus a self-identification flag. Output lists each candidate as its name and whether it was admitted.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "no_filter",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "anything"
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=anything included=true\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "filter",
        "mode": "self_agent",
        "containers": [
          {
            "name": "agent",
            "is_self_agent": true
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "container=agent included=true\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature2_1_env_credentials:
{
  "description": "Building an encoded registry credential token from credentials supplied through the environment. When both a user name and a password are provided through their respective environment variables, the toolkit assembles an auth object and emits its transport encoding: the Base64 of a compact JSON document carrying the user name and password fields. When either the user name or the password is missing, no token can be produced and a neutral missing-credentials error category is reported instead. Output is either the encoded token or the neutral error line.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "env_auth",
        "user": "user-a",
        "pass": "pass-a"
      },
      "expected_output": "token=eyJ1c2VybmFtZSI6InVzZXItYSIsInBhc3N3b3JkIjoicGFzcy1hIn0=\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "env_auth",
        "user": "",
        "pass": ""
      },
      "expected_output": "error=missing_credentials\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature2_2_server_address:
{
  "description": "Extracting the registry server component from a container image reference. The reference is first parsed; the server component is then taken to be the substring up to the first path separator of the parsed reference. A fully qualified reference whose leading component is a host name yields that host name; a reference whose leading component is an organization (no host) yields that organization name. An input that cannot be parsed as a reference (for example, the empty string) reports a neutral invalid-reference error category. Output is either the extracted server component or the neutral error line.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "parse_server",
        "ref": "example.com/lib/app"
      },
      "expected_output": "server=example.com\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "parse_server",
        "ref": ""
      },
      "expected_output": "error=invalid_reference\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_1_docker_env:
{
  "description": "Translating command-line connection options into the environment variables that configure the daemon API client. Three options may be supplied: a daemon host address, a boolean verify-TLS switch, and an API version. With no options supplied the host falls back to its built-in default socket address and the verify-TLS variable is left unset (empty). When a custom host is supplied it is propagated verbatim, and when the verify-TLS switch is enabled the corresponding variable is set to the string flag value. Output reports the resolved host and the resolved verify-TLS variable.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "docker_env"
      },
      "expected_output": "docker_host=unix:///var/run/docker.sock\ndocker_tls_verify=\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "docker_env",
        "host": "some-custom-docker-host",
        "tlsverify": true,
        "api_version": "1.99"
      },
      "expected_output": "docker_host=some-custom-docker-host\ndocker_tls_verify=1\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_2_secret_from_file:
{
  "description": "Resolving a sensitive option value that may be supplied either inline or as a reference to a file holding the secret. The resolver inspects the configured value: if it names an existing file on disk, the value is replaced by the trimmed contents of that file; otherwise the inline string is kept as-is. The first case supplies the secret directly as a literal string. The second case supplies the secret indirectly through a file whose contents become the resolved value. Output reports the resolved secret value.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "secret_resolve",
        "value": "supersecretstring"
      },
      "expected_output": "secret=supersecretstring\n"
    },
    {
      "input": {
        "action": "secret_resolve",
        "file_content": "megasecretstring"
      },
      "expected_output": "secret=megasecretstring\n"
    }
  ]
}
